name: Elizabeth Laskowski
tweet: Concerns are understandable. Vaccine development can take more than 10 years, so each new vaccine that is recommended comes out only after extensive research and testing. As technology has improved, we have been able to develop new vaccines, which has led to the increase.

name: Elizabeth Laskowski
tweet: You're welcome! Microbiology and infectious disease is my field of study and something I'm passionate about, so I want to educate others.

name: Elizabeth Laskowski
tweet: The letters A, B, and C refer to the serogroups of the bacteria that are covered by the individual vaccine. Each bacteria within a species can express different proteins or carbohydrates that serve as antigens. These types of antigens are grouped into serogroups for the vaccine.

name: Elizabeth Laskowski
tweet: 2) There are 2 types of meningitis, bacterial and viral. Within that, many pathogens can lead to meningitis. The meningococcal vaccine protects against the most common bacterial form that kills in hours to a day. Other bacteria are less common and viral is almost never fatal.

name: Elizabeth Laskowski
tweet: 1) Disease will always have an uncertain course in some patients, but for the very VERY vast majority, vaccination provides the primary immune response necessary for a successful secondary immune response should they be exposed.

name: Elizabeth Laskowski
tweet: Except that is not how pathogens nor immunity work. Vaccines contain pieces of the pathogen to build memory B cells, but not enough to infect. Without vaccines, we would have to get sick with the pathogen in order to build immunity. That risks permanent effects and death.

name: Elizabeth Laskowski
tweet: As someone who has a degree in microbiology with a focus in infectious disease, I had to spend significant time reading the research and learning how our bodies respond to vaccines. I also had to learn the chemistry behind them, so I know what the ingredients are! Vaccines work.
